name: Quick Pouch Mini
description:
Quick Pouch Mini

1. Check filter for water (at air regulator) – excess water build up may indicate a supply problem. 
2. Clean any debris from machine. 
3. Wipe down product contact surfaces with approved cleaner per requirements.  4. Check Safety Security.

On the first working day of each week:
1. Check the Teflon tape for discoloration. If the tape is beginning to appear lighter, replace.
2. Check drive wheels for glazing. Lightly scuff with fine Scotchbrite to remove glaze.

On the first working day of each month:
1. Check all electrical connections. 
2. Tighten bolts on moving parts. 
3. Check the timing belt and all other belts on the machine for tension and wear. If the belts show wear, replace them."

======================================
Annually - 1. Clean/Replace the filter/regulator cartridge.

Every 2 yrs - 1. Replace PLC lithium battery.

name: PureTec RO/DI Water System
description:
Maintenance
========================================================
(a1) 14" MIXED Bed - change when QC light turns red or below 1M(ohm) on M3300 control panel.
(a2) 14" MIXED Bed - same as (a1), CHECK all gauges on flow (compounding) RO/DI sheet check for unusual reading
(b1) SODIUM Tank, water test weekly; replace tank once a month or less than 3ppm so it doesn’t damage membrane.
(b2) Carbon Tank - replace once every 6 months.
(c1) UV light must be changed after 8000 hours or when light turns RED.
(d1) R.O. Filter replace monthly.
(e1) Water flow pressure gauge , needs to be a 50/50 ratio (currently 1:8 each)
(f1) membranes recommended year to be replaced, (if not water flow/pressure isn't balanced and will drop in flow)
(g1) Reserve Tank – Needs to be sanitized once a year and inspected for leaks/cracks once a month.
(h1) Water pump – Needs to be serviced once a year and inspected for leaks/cracks once a month.
(i1) micron filters , replace yearly (2 micron, 1 micron.)
(Control Panel) Wipe down and remove dust once a month. Notes: Drop under 1 ohm, need to replace (a1) and (a2), After sanitizing, the control panel needs to be re calibrated (need to for older PureTec models will need a 14” mixed to sanitize system.
========================================================
As Required
*Change mixed bed tank (end of batch when conductivity light goes out)
*Check for leaks.

Monthly
*Check the UV lamp counter. Record the lamp time in the maintenance log. Replace the
UV lamp every 8000 hours or 24 months, whichever comes first.

Two Months
Lab test water purity per this procedure.

Yearly
1. Sanitize the system using “Minncare” or an equivalent cold sterilizer.*
2. Clean or replace the quartz sleeve in the UV filter.*
3. Replace all water filter elements (3).
========================================================

name: Image Scanner
description:
Scanner

To ensure the proper functioning of a N7100E document scanner, it is recommended to perform the following maintenance tasks regularly:
1.	Cleaning: Regularly clean the exterior and interior of the scanner, including the scanning glass, rollers, and feeder. Use a soft, lint-free cloth to prevent scratches on the glass surface.
2.	Calibration: Periodically calibrate the scanner to maintain accurate scans. Calibration helps align the optical sensors, ensuring that images are captured correctly and without distortion.
3.	Software updates: Check for software updates regularly to keep the scanner running smoothly and to take advantage of any performance enhancements or bug fixes.
4.	Roller replacement: The rollers in the feeder can wear out over time and may need to be replaced. Check the rollers periodically for signs of wear, such as cracks or flat spots, and replace them as needed.
5.	Dust and debris removal: Dust and debris can accumulate inside the scanner, causing misfeeds and jams. Open the scanner periodically to remove any debris that has accumulated inside.
6.	Preventive maintenance: Regular preventive maintenance, such as oiling the rollers, can extend the lifespan of the scanner and prevent issues down the line. Consult the manufacturer's instructions for recommended preventive maintenance procedures.
By following these maintenance steps, you can ensure that your N7100E document scanner continues to perform reliably for many years to come.

name: Building 1671/ 1661  - Dock Doors
description:
1. Lubricate Moving Parts - use "Silicone Grease Lubrication"

Hinges, Rollers, allowing it to travel up and down along the tracks, making sure doors move smoothly. Apply lubricant to Hinges and pivot points. 

2. Clear Debris From tracks 

Cleaning tracks to reduce potential damage. Wipe down with soft clothes while doors are closed. 

3. Tighten any loose Bolts

Inspect brackets and Hinges, for wear and tear or loose components making sure everything is moving safely. 

4. Check All Pulleys and Cables for Wear and Tear  "Replace worn out cables"

5. Look for Damaged parts 

Check out Rollers,  Hardware,  Bolts, Hinges, and other metal parts for rust. Replace Damaged panels that affects opening and closing sections. Inspect weather seals on bottom section for damages, replace I'd needed.  

Report or for any serious replacement parts or damages.

name: Building 1671/1661  -  Exterior Man Doors
description:
1. Lubricate hinges with W-40, allowing the door to travel freely making sure it moves smoothly. 

2. Add Graphite lubricant to door latch and keyhole

3. Tighten any loose Bolts - Inspect brackets and Hinges, for wear and tear or loose components making sure everything is moving safely. 

4. Check door close for ware and tear - inspect that the door close slowly and all the way. 

5. Look for Damaged parts 

Check hardware, bolts, hinges, and other metal parts for rust. Inspect weather seals on bottom section for damages, replace if needed.  

Report or for any serious replacement parts or damages.

name: Fire Extinguishers
description:
We currently have 15 fire extinguishers available, their locations are indicated on the facility map provided. Please note that the last inspection was conducted on 2/22/2024, with three extinguishers (#12, #13, #14) having undergone a 5-year inspection. The remaining extinguishers will require a 12-year inspection in February 2028.
=========================================================
Monthly Checks:

    Visual Inspection: Look for any signs of physical damage, corrosion, or blockage in the nozzle.
    Pressure: Check that the pressure gauge is in the operable range or the indicator is in the green zone.
    Seals & Tamper Indicators: Ensure the safety seals and tamper indicators are not broken or missing.
    Accessibility: Verify the extinguisher is in its designated place, visible, and accessible.

Annual Maintenance (By a Professional):

    Thorough Examination: Conduct a more detailed check for damage or corrosion.
    Operational Testing: Test or inspect the extinguisher's mechanical parts and operating mechanisms to ensure proper function.
    Discharge Test (if applicable): Some types of extinguishers may require a discharge test at certain intervals (e.g., every 5 to 12 years, depending on the extinguisher type) to ensure they properly expel the extinguishing agent.
    Refilling: After any use or as needed following the manufacturer's instructions.
    Record Keeping: Document the maintenance, including any services performed or parts replaced.

5-Year Maintenance:

    Internal Examination: For certain types of extinguishers, such as dry chemical extinguishers, an internal examination is required every 5 to 6 years.

12-Year Hydrostatic Testing:

    Hydrostatic Testing: Required for most types of extinguishers at 12-year intervals. This test involves pressurizing the extinguisher to a higher pressure than normal to ensure the integrity of the cylinder.

===================================
Fire Extinguishers Training Video - https://gotsafety.vhx.tv/manufacturing-fire-extinguisher-safety/season:1/videos/fire-extinguishers-1
